# .NET Framework → .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

## Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+. It's completely removed.
2. **`ThreadAbortException` will never be thrown** — the `catch` block is dead code.
3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`**.

## Why `Thread.Abort()` Was Removed

It was inherently unsafe — it could interrupt code mid-execution (inside locks, during I/O, in `finally` blocks), causing corrupted state, leaked resources, and deadlocks. .NET Core replaced it with **cooperative cancellation**.

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cooperative cancellation requested — clean up
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit loop cleanly; no ResetAbort needed
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);

        // Signal cancellation (cooperative — the loop checks the token)
        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait for graceful shutdown with a timeout
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't finish in time — log a warning.
            // In .NET 8 there is NO way to forcibly kill it.
            Log.Warning("Worker did not shut down within timeout");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _workerTask?.Wait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## If You Can't Make Methods Async

If `GetNextItem()` is a synchronous blocking call you don't control:

```csharp
private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        try
        {
            // Option A: poll with timeout instead of indefinite block
            if (!TryGetNextItem(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(1), out var item))
                continue;

            token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
            ProcessItem(item);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            break;
        }
        finally
        {
            FlushBuffers();
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **`Thread.Abort` compiles but throws at runtime** | No compiler warning — you get `PlatformNotSupportedException` only when the line executes |
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | A `Socket.Read()` or `Console.ReadLine()` won't respond to `CancellationToken`. Refactor to async or use timeout-based polling |
| **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` is dead code** | It silently disappears — no error, no cleanup, no rollback |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | It can't wake a blocked thread. `CancellationToken` integrates with `async`, `WaitHandle`, and polling |
| **No forced termination exists** | If a worker ignores the token, you cannot kill it. Design all work to be cancellation-aware |
| **`Thread.Sleep` → `Task.Delay`** | `Thread.Sleep` blocks a thread pool thread; `Task.Delay` is non-blocking and accepts a `CancellationToken` |

## Migration Checklist

1. Replace `Thread` + `volatile bool` → `Task` + `CancellationTokenSource`
2. Delete `Thread.Abort()`, `Thread.ResetAbort()`, `catch (ThreadAbortException)`
3. Add `catch (OperationCanceledException)` with token guard
4. Thread the `CancellationToken` through **every** blocking/async call
5. Convert `Stop()` to `async Task StopAsync()` with timeout
6. Implement `IDisposable` to clean up the `CancellationTokenSource`
